text:
the #metoo movement in india is gaining momentum for the past few weeks. i see some people expressing what’s called “movement fatigue” when a novel social change wears out after a while and people grow tired out of it. i get it. the changes happen in waves and not all at once. our minds would have moved on to new stuffs by the time the next wave hits.
.
in your fatigue, don’t discourage or stop those who are telling the truth. if not for anything, just listen, read their stories and learn. by telling their stories, each person is peeling one layer off of the complex social stratification that’s unique to india.
.
it is quite interesting to see how so many factors silently played out for years(centuries even) before the few seconds of abuse happened. it is even more interesting to see new factors coming into play when the truth is out loud crying for attention. analyze. over think these things! these are our chances to evolve in modern world! .
i hope we all raise together during movements like this and not topple into the fatigue.

text:
i won’t show the pictures of my ptsd episode that that fucker sent me down into looked like because even for me they are too vulnerable to share.
but while i was trying to hold in a full on breakdown, (and still having one nonetheless) on the the subway, one person on the train offered me kleenex and as i tried to pull one out and give them the rest of the package back they kindly shook their head indicating that i could keep the rest. then a young 20 something girl pulled out of her bag a chocolate bar and said she didn’t said it was a little early for halloween and wasn’t sure if i believed in it all the while i’m crying and have tears streaming down my face and semi hyperventilating and she revealed to me her mom had cancer and went on to tell me she met her celeb crush the other day and that they have been texting which is crazy to her. she said no matter how dark things are now, things will  get better no matter how bad they seem. .
.
.
i’m always astonished by the random act of strangers on new york subways are when i have complete breakdown on the subway. they’re always offset by my ptsd because i have major dissociative episodes related to my trauma where i either dissociate and become unresponsive and i can’t move or i just break down and start crying and can’t function. i’m angry that something so simple could set me off so much. i felt ashamed and angry that something that happens to women so often- such a tiny micro aggression that we as people that walk the earth that are perceived as women (whether we identify as them or not)get sexually harassed on a daily basis are used to this type of behavior but because of my ptsd and events that have shaped me into who i am would trigger me so much to fall in such a delicate place in which i was barely able to function and had to meet someone new and had a great effect on my future and my potential to find a new job. i told myself kindly in my head to not judge my emotions and that i’m allowed to feel the way that i feel and that made me cry even harder because it is fine it’s fine for me to feel offended and violated and to feel those memories and remember the things {cont in comments} #miaw18

text:
no one can tell you what is painful to you. what may have no effect on one person may be devastating to another. the most important thing is ... if it is hurtful and/or harmful to you then it’s not good for you! you have a right to guard your psychological safety. don’t let anyone make you feel bad for expressing what’s best for you.
.
.
.

text:
@regran_ed from @whywomendontleave -  this is an excellent description.  when i was married to my abuser the word narcissist wasn't commonly used. it wasn't until the end of my marriage that i started hearing and reading about the narcissist.  i am sure my ex-husband meets the criteria for being a narcissist, he also meets the criteria for being a sociopath as well. however since i am not a doctor i can't actually say for sure. truthfully i don't really care what his problem is.  i don't mean to sound heartless because there was a time i cared very much.  i cared more than anyone for years and years. but eventually i had to make a choice, him or me. it came down to survival. and i choose to survive, and for my kids to survive. it's important to educate yourself about the hows and whys your partner can be so heartless and cruel. it is important to know what you're dealing with and up against. just don't get too hung up on labels. at the end of the day what really matters is that you are safe physically and emotionally, and your children are as well.  if you're dealing with a narcissist or recovering from one, have faith. it won't always hurt, it does get better. it does take a long time but you can heal. you can rebuild and love again. i know because i am doing it. and if i can do it, anyone can 💜

text:
🔦 program spotlight: understanding integrative mental healthcare: a balance of art, science, and re-writing our stories
.
.
the nj center for the healing arts is one now considered to be one of the first integrative mental health centers in the country, but what is integrative mental health? how does it differ from conventional approaches? join our founder and director, carol veizer, for a brief explanation of the philosophy behind integrative mental healthcare and how it is practiced within our center. this will be an interactive discussion, so there will be ample time for questions and answers.
.
.

text: ❤️ i'm all in for #womenempowernent #empoweringwomen on this #feninistfriday. it's time we allow ourselves to own our stories and our voices! it's time we empower one another to harness our inner strength to undo the oppression and systematic patriarchy that has been imposed on us.  i'm leu of the current events; the power that we as women yield in our voices and in our ability to band together, will be our weapon for cataclysm. i'm so here for us finding our ground and owning our past no matter how bleak, dark or colorful.  i'm here to say #believesurvivors. i'm here to say #metoo. i'm here for the #metoomovement but what's disheartening is the push back that we receive from our abusers, from those who don't believe us and those who are in power. as of to say someone voicing their trauma is a outcry for attention. as if someone would take pleasure in professing that they've been victimized in such an inhumane way. this is not the time to ridicule survivors. this is not the time to find fallacies in their stories to paint out to be liars. this is not the time to put those in power above yet again while abolishing any notions that they could have harmed another human being.  #metoo started from a powerful woman of color tarana burke who wanted to help woman who were survivors of sexual violence. it's been over 10 years since she created the movement and was vocal about the work she had been doing. the #metoomovement is still relevant today because of the monsters that live in our society. however the #metoomovement is not just exclusive to women in hollywood, it's inclusive of woman of color #woc, the homeless, the youth, the #lgbt, the elderly and others who aren't given the opportunity to make themselves heard or who society has forgotten about.  yet in the event that a survivor vocalizes their abuse and or abuser their oftentimes instantly martyred, accosted, forced to face arbitration ; as if someone else can tell them that their experiences are valid and worth rectifying. forcing these survivors to go to trial and look their abusers in the face while they testify against them. having a judge and juror  announce whether they're contempt and often l

text:
i wrote the following blog post exactly one year ago. i am posting it again on my professional blog, because i believe this conversation is just as important today as it was last year. given what has just gone on in the united states, we have witnessed again, just how badly the system needs to change. my heart goes out to dr. ford for being so brave and to anyone that was triggered by the recent events. take good care of yourselves. it is important in times like these when we feel helpless, to really focus on our own healing, it will have a ripple effect on the collective. thank you for reading 🌹
•
“pay attention to your inner voice, your body and listen to what it is telling you. when we can do that, when we can heal ourselves, i believe it will start to heal the culture as a collective.”
•
to read the full post, click on the link in my profile! ❤️
•

text:
“public interest is a priority”
to protect and serve with fairness the public interest we need to implement two views :  bipartisanship , and check and balance by the other party. 
bipartisanship works , it gets the two parties to agree on mid points to reach a solution to a problem. it removes stubbornness and replace it by mutual respect. if both parties agree , and the majority held by one party, then we still need to have the opponent party existence to get this agreed solution into action.  we are living in chaos , and the focus on the people’s interest is taking less attention , and more attention toward protecting the party’s power. 
when one party dominate, it will result in over power, increase in the number of  voiceless people who become afraid to raise their voice or lose hope in justice.  we are experiencing this now in humanity matters, like separating the families at the border that resulted in ( 450 children as of now , still not reunified with their parents. the kavanaugh nomination and the push to confirm by one party, and not listening to the other parties of fair request of thorough , and enough time investigation, that negatively affected all sexually abused survivors, leading to increase the number of “voiceless” due to hopeless feeling in justice system. 
for mid term election , candidates are running on major matters, like health care , education , safety , environment and labor union. “the candidates are running on health care costs — a defining issue for democrats this year — and issues like gun control and the environment, on which the national republican party has shifted right even as the district has migrated left.” (i) 
health care cost and medicare /medicaid is a big concern for many especially for retired who doesn’t want to experience a rise in their out of the pocket expense, covering preexisting condition is another big fear among the public.  the recent fail by the senate democrat to block trump’s short term health plan. “these junk insurance plans can deny health care coverage to people with pre-existing conditions when they need it the most,” said sen. tammy baldwin (d-wis.)” (ii) .  preexisting condition needs to be(con

text:
one of the wild damiana bushes in full bloom during this year’s summer season!
endemic to texas, yet found here in lower california (mexico), damiana is a small yellow-flowered shrub with long, light-green leaves. it has a wonderful aromatic odor and contains a warm yet bitter, camphor-like tasting oil.
the oils from the damiana leaves have been adored by many for their acclaimed sexually rejuvenating properties. furthermore, there has been strong claims that damiana can be very effective in improving asthma, anxiety, headaches, constipation and many many more! 😍🌱

text:
the #metoo movement has opened a lot of conversations everywhere and i feel i need to come out with my experience as well.
this incident happened to me in ganga ram hospital, new delhi in 2002. 
i was 16 years old and i was confused about myself regarding my sexuality and i thought of meeting an experienced psychologist to discuss it with as i was crying out for help and had to keep it a secret. i booked an appointment with dr. j.m. wadhawan as he was a senior consultant in psychiatry at ganga ram at that time. 
i reached the private opd and i was next to go in. i went inside and with great difficulty i asked him if there was something wrong with me. i remember the discussion going on for a few minutes and then he asked me to get up on the bench where we wanted to examine my reflexes. he took a hammer and checked my leg reflexes and all that. 
he asked me to take my clothes off and lie down on the small bench with a thin mattress where patients are examined. i was lying down in my underwear, in confusion as to how was this related to being consulted or a reflex check up.
he then started to rub his hands sexually around my chest and nipples. i could see his expressions change. he started to breathe deeply and heavily, in complete lust, and then he went further south with his hand. he started to rub my genitals with my briefs on and at that moment i sensed that he is just lusting out and not really consulting me. 
i quickly got up, wore my clothes and left the room. i couldn't complain to the hospital as i was ashamed of myself and didn't want my parents to find out at that time about me visiting a psychiatrist. attaching a photo of the doctor. he is still practicing at ganga ram and other speciality clinics.
#metoomovement #himtoo

text: hi everybody! with mental health day and national coming out day and the me too movement i've been feeling kind of overwhelmed. i'm still working on my mental health, i'm still recovering my personal power from sexual abuse, and i'm still learning to embrace my ever deepening queerness, my people loving sexuality! it feels like a constant process and sometimes i just need to turn off all those thoughts, take a walk in the woods and watch the changing leaves. how they rustle in the breeze, branches swaying back and forth slowly, jewel tones of abundance, highlighting the gems to be found in letting go. all around the world old men are still using and abusing, taking advantage of systems that are there only to serve their selfish pursuits, and all around the world brave women, courageous gender fluid and non-binary people, shining trans folk, and bright children are coming forward, owning who they are, stepping out of hiding and into their personal power, celebrating themselves and their life! you all give me hope every day for this brighter future we're all building together outside of these decrepit failing systems. i have hope in my heart, i have light in my eyes, i feel yours and see yours shining too! we're going to get through this together and though the trees may look bare in the approaching season, trust they will bud come spring anew! #mentalhealthawareness #nationalcomingoutday #metoo #nature #beauty #hope #love

text_retweet:
reposted from @realamericannews -  an illegal alien from el salvador, who was previously deported from the u.s., was charged with the rape and a list of other charges after a woman in long island, new york, was attacked, beaten unconscious and was then raped.⁣
⁣
ever martinez-reyes, 24, was charged with rape, sexual assault, and other assault charges, and ordered to be held without bail at a saturday arraignment, fox news reported. martinez-reyes allegedly followed his female target around until he felt like he could get away with raping her, according to police. martinez-reyes originally entered the country illegally in 2010 before he was deported, however he illegally entered the u.s. again in 2014.⁣
⁣
“when he assaulted her and knocked her out, he then proceeded to rape her,” nassau police commissioner patrick ryder told newsday. “she woke up and he knocked her out again and viciously continued to assault her.”⁣
⁣
according to police, the victim came to after being knocked out by martinez-reyes and realized she was being raped. martinez-reyes then reportedly got up and ran. the victim had a broken jaw and was taken to the hospital after calling the police.⁣
⁣
martinez-reyes faces up to 25 years in prison, if convicted.⁣
⁣

text:
1/7

in 2006, tarana burke started the #metoo movement as a way to create a dialogue and support system for survivors within communities of color. in 2017, the movement went viral. a massive online campaign lead to a groundswell of individuals from every gender, race, and sexuality sharing their stories of survival. though it’s empowering to see perpetrators being held accountable, it has been re-traumatizing for so many. “if you make something [like this] viral, you have to be prepared to help people deal,” burke said. “you have to give people something else besides the disclosure.” this year has been a whirlwind. however, the movement is not perfect, and we are not perfect. we want to acknowledge the challenges of all this attention, and get back to burke’s original intention: to start a conversation so that survivors can feel heard, validated, and supported.

to survivors: awakenings hears you, believes you, and supports you. it is hard enough to survive assault or abuse, let alone an entire year of re-traumatizing public scrutiny. to help you heal, we have events and workshops that span every modality of creative healing that we can think of. give it a try. but we also want to know: what do you need from us? how can we do better to support you?

to the greater community: we know the epidemic of sexual violence feels insurmountable. but there are ways you can make a difference: by supporting survivors. if you want to have a positive impact on a survivor’s life, come find us. volunteer, donate, or even share this video. starting a conversation about sexual assault with one person could make a difference. so start now.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text: if anyone knows me at all, i don’t ever voice my opinion about politics because of this. maybe i shouldn’t say anything knowing the outcome. also, i have not educated myself enough to feel like my opinion would matter. however, more than ever, i am aware that my voice matters as much as anyone else’s. not even one minute after i made this comment, this person came on assuming i was looking for a fight. this is truly saddening and rather than fight back, i will continue to kill them with kindness because we could use as much as we can.

text:
the internal revolution:
(i'm using "women" & "men" here in the interest of expedience, but these words are only markers used to keep this concise. substitute feminine/masculine, yin/yang, or whatever feels right to you in the reading of this.) before a woman speaks, she must decide three things, all of which are revolutionary, & often all of which remain largely below the level of her consciousness during the “decision” process:
.

1.	that her experience matters
.
2.	that she has a voice
.
3.	that she is allowed to speak about her experience.
.
.
patriarchal dominator paradigms (such as the one that is currently dying a slow & ignominious death all around us) rest on a few principles that go largely unspoken but are understood at a visceral level by everyone participating, & when those principles are violated, the select revolutionaries who have violated the unspoken rules are raked across the coals for a parade of various “reasons” which are not actually the real reasons, but are touted as such.
.
.
in this case, here are the 3 principles i wish to highlight for you today, along with the underpinning line of patriarchal dominator thinking that supports these principles:
.
. 1. women do not have experience. 
women do not matter & are irrelevant, except for the furtherance of the human race (i.e. as uteruses) & as objects for men’s desires. this means that women’s experiences do not matter, because women don’t have experiences (apart from men). only subjects can have experiences. women are objects. therefore they do not have experience.
.
.
2. women do not have voices. 
women are decorative only & serve a very specific & limited function in relation to men. uteruses don’t have voices. decorations don’t have voices. women do not exist otherwise, & therefore do not have voices.
.
.
3. women do not speak about their experience. .
since they don’t have voices (#2) & don’t have experiences (#1), there is no possible way they could speak about their experiences.
.
.

when a woman like anita hill, or dr. blasey ford, (or any of the women we don’t know who have said #metoo) decides to speak up about her experience, she must first (cntd in comments)

text:
5/7

in 2006, tarana burke started the #metoo movement as a way to create a dialogue and support system for survivors within communities of color. in 2017, the movement went viral. a massive online campaign lead to a groundswell of individuals from every gender, race, and sexuality sharing their stories of survival. though it’s empowering to see perpetrators being held accountable, it has been re-traumatizing for so many. “if you make something [like this] viral, you have to be prepared to help people deal,” burke said. “you have to give people something else besides the disclosure.” this year has been a whirlwind. however, the movement is not perfect, and we are not perfect. we want to acknowledge the challenges of all this attention, and get back to burke’s original intention: to start a conversation so that survivors can feel heard, validated, and supported.

to survivors: awakenings hears you, believes you, and supports you. it is hard enough to survive assault or abuse, let alone an entire year of re-traumatizing public scrutiny. to help you heal, we have events and workshops that span every modality of creative healing that we can think of. give it a try. but we also want to know: what do you need from us? how can we do better to support you?

to the greater community: we know the epidemic of sexual violence feels insurmountable. but there are ways you can make a difference: by supporting survivors. if you want to have a positive impact on a survivor’s life, come find us. volunteer, donate, or even share this video. starting a conversation about sexual assault with one person could make a difference. so start now.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
one of my favorite halloween’s i was a nun. my friend jessi @jbird_sparkleshark dressed as a dude & her costume was so good that i didn’t recognize her at first. i had a leather riding crop with a heart on it and i was saving people’s souls by spanking the demons out of them but this “dude” wouldn’t leave me alone. he kept saying crude things and i really wanted to punch him for making passes at me... then i realized it was jessi!
now i understand something that most women experience all the time. i hope and think that #metoo is helping to wake many men up to this sad reality of our culture. jessi is delightfully beautiful & it was fun to see her flip the roles & be the aggressor as a dude.
role playing can be great therapy & healing can be fun❤️
halloween is supposed to be a time where we do things totally out of our comfort zone. where we celebrate our follies as humans, and the absurdities of societal structures (much like carnival and also related but that’s another story).
it used to be called all thieves day & was a time when the peasants got revenge on the rich people. not too different than the christmas carol “bring us some bread and pudding” when peasants would sing to the rich and the rich would feed them, this is where trick or treat came from.
more than any of that, it is new years to the people of the north because they believe the new year starts in the dark of winter like babies in the womb or seeds in the ground. at midnight is a time when we they let go of the souls of loved ones who have passed in the previous year as the saints open a door to the underworld. the masking is also meant as an opportunity for the recently deceased to join us in revelry before going into the afterlife, a moment when the living and dead can party together...
then come all souls day, day of dead. as a folklorist, i could make a hundred posts on the deep cultural, historical, and spiritual significance.
make halloween sacred & special in some way. step out of your comfort zone and play, become the spirit of all those things you suppress, all the things that are dying and that you wish to let go of.
i love this time of year! #nun #halloween

text: so this post is going to be a little different than my typical happy and positive ones. i have read up on the #metoo movement which adresses sexual assault victims! i wanted to share an experience i have had that is very similar to others that i have read. i really debated posting this and i am nervous to do so but more women need to be heard, men need to be taught that no means no and maybe, just maybe, my story will be that story to change the way one man thinks about women. we are not objects. okay here we go, throwing it back to grade 10. i had i think maybe 1 “boyfriend” before this and had my first kiss in grade 9. but besides that nothing, during elementary school and first year high school i was focused on school and sports. so in grade 10 i met this boy, which was a cousin of a good friend of mine at the time. we dated maybe a month and then this one day happened. i remember we were watching a show and he asked me to do some sexual things. i had said no i don’t want to do that, not comfortable with that (15 years old, innocent, not wanting anything to do with that). well let me tell you, he did not like that answer and tried sweet talking me into doing stuff. all i really remember is saying no again and i was forced to do it. he grabbed my hand and made me touch him, and yes i did try to pull away. as for me, well he forced his hand in places that i was not comfortable with, again, i tried to push his hand away too. this guy was the most manipulative person i have ever met. he always talked down to me, shaming my body, shaming the way i look, my personality, my energy, etc. why didn’t i stop him? well i tried to! with my words (which hello men, if she says no, it means no), with some force by trying to push his hands away or pull my hand away but he was bigger than me, 6.2 and almost 200lbs. i’m 5.4 and 115lbs for reference. i felt trapped. he was my bf, why did i feel so uncomfortable with this? in my mind all the thoughts were running through... such as “why won’t he listen to me saying no, if i don’t let him do this without complaining.. (continued in the comments)

text:
hace casi un mes que @jaricurbaez se encontró a una gatita cerca de donde paseamos al perro todos los días. ella corría hacia  los brazos de mi esposa a recibir mimos  y aunque la gente de la calle le daba comida a ella y a los demás gatos de la cuadra ( casi todos machos ), nosotras le llevábamos alimento también. 
yo no quería encariñarme mucho porque ya teníamos dos mascotas en casa, pero un día decidimos que teníamos que operarla porque la podía  preñar “don gato y su pandilla”. se dejó llevar docilmente al carro y sin chistar entró y  para que pudiéramos al  día siguiente llevarla al shelter para que la ligaran. la bañamos y le cortamos las uñitas y nos dimos cuenta que “la flaquita” ( así le pusimos ) tenía varias heridas. también nos dimos cuenta que no era una gata callejera por lo dócil y tranquila y porque no más pisó nuestro apartamento, prácticamente sabía donde quedaba todo...hasta el baño de jasper! allí mismo fue a orinar sin pedir permiso. 
la flaquita entró como gata por su casa, se montó en el mueble y casi nos dice: “por favor prendan la tele y pónganme ’my cat from hell’”...
obviamente no tuvimos corazón para devolverla a la calle. 
jasper la quiere “montar” todo el día a pesar que él -notieneconqué-😩🤬 y como buen niño malcriado le hace bullying...(ya tuvo su time out y sus cholazos respectivos por acosador sexual #metoo 👟💨🙀🙀🙀) pero poco a poco nos vamos adaptando. 🤒nuestra flaquis aún está muy débil y tiene parásitos, pero gracias al dr. paco, pronto se recuperará...
quiere dormir con nosotras y pasamos dos días sin pegar un ojo bajándola de la cama. pero creo que ya aprendió o no nos hemos dado cuenta.
así que, ahora tenemos una nena: “la flaquita” silva urbaez o urbaez silva, porque aquí te somos democráticos...😍❤️😂😂😂😻 #momsgirl #yasomos4 #lafamiliacrece #somosunclichélésbico #crazycatladies 😻😾🐶 #jasperquiereconlaflaca

text:
عام انقضى على فضح هارفي واينستين، وكل يوم تقريبًا مر منذ أكتوبر 2017 شهد سقوط متحرش جديد. غالبية هؤلاء من الفنانين والصحفيين والإعلاميين والسياسيين. حكايات سهلة وبسيطة بتركيبة شعبية: رجل شهير يتمتع بالسلطة والمال، يتحرش بفتاة أقل شهرة منه أو تشغل مرتبة وظيفية أدنى. الصورة المثالية والتقليدية للجلاد والضحية، لكن الأخيرة فهمت أن مغازلتها في مكان العمل بغير رضاها «تحرش»، ومطالبتها بمقابل جنسي لأي خدمة وظيفية «تحرش»، ولمس جسدها عنوة أو حتى تحت تأثير الخوف أيضًا «تحرش». لعل هذا كان المكسب الأول للحراك. المكسب الثاني كان سقوط حاجز الخوف، الخوف من الحديث بمباشرة فجة عن لمس الأعضاء الحميمة لدى النساء، عن الاستمناء أمامهن، عن ولوجهن غصبًا. أما المكسب الثالث فكان كسر الهالة المحيطة بالرجل، الرجل بحد ذاته ككائن أكثر قوة من المرأة، حجمًا ومكانة وسلطة، وككائن قادر على التحرش أو الاغتصاب أو السيطرة دون أن يتعرض للعقاب، ما دامت المنظومة تحميه وتبرر له جرائمه علنًا وفي السر.

كل ما جاء بعد ذلك كان تفاصيل إضافية. الحكايات والشهادات على اختلافها وفظاعتها شكَّلت ملامح مرحلة تاريخية جديدة في التعامل مع النساء، مع سلطتهن الوحيدة والكاملة على أجسادهن. ما كان يُعد كلامًا شخصيًّا وخاصًّا ذاب في الفضاء العام وتحول إلى نقاش عالمي.
.
#منشور #تحرش #النساء #الرجال #العالم #العقاب #الجريمة #me_too #metoo
name: منشور - Manshoor

text:
listing few facts from hinduism:
1. hinduism has more number of female goddess than the male counterparts which represents shakti, wisdom, wealth, etc.;
2. we cite our planet as 'mother earth';
3. we refer animals with a sense of gratitude as 'गाय माता' who just gives us selflessly without asking anything in return;
4. our mere existence in this universe is because a female - my mother gave me birth.
.
at a time when the whole nation is worshiping women deity in the form 'ma durga', the timing of recent events seems no odd. the #metoo moment is a fierce representation of the women voicing their concerns fearlessly.
.
i fail to understand, in a country where women figures are worshipped as god then-
why are they ill-treated in the first place?
why are they not respected?
infact i am even bewildered by the thought that do we even need a term - 'feminism' when a women figure is given so much empowerment in our religion?
.
i felt obnoxious and was left in despair when i read the description given by a few and by the thought of it i couldn't imagine the excruciating pain that they would have gone through. i wish this navratri, 'ma durga' gives  courage, empathy and empowerment to all the women out there to destroy the demons roaming freely.
.
i wish these illuminated street lights enlightens our thoughts and i urge everyone to celebrate this festival in a more meaningful way by creating this world as a beautiful place to live for everyone! 🙏 jai bhavani! jai ambey! 🙏
